ome American. Throughout the 1930s and 1940s, radio created a virtual place where Jewish immigrants could listen to voices like theirs and affirm the sound of their community as it evolved, particularly in light of World War II and the years that followed.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aMass mediazUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aRadio broadcasting, YiddishzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRadio programszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTheater, YiddishzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aGeneral. 4aJudaism. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aKelman, Ari Y., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025573940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094389640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943896423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943896/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles